Keishia Taylor, Socialist Party (ISA in Ireland)The 1918-1919 “Spanish Flu” killed between 50-100 million people, more than the number of deaths in the First and Second World Wars combined.
Only the press in neutral Spain reported on the outbreak, giving the flu its name.
As mass graves were dug, schools closed and public gatherings banned, one newspaper announced “This is not a public health measure.
Public HealthThe global devastation caused by the Spanish flu had a profound impact on the consciousness of working people across the world.
All the medical advances of the last hundred years cannot overcome chronic underfunding and understaffing of the public health system.